abstract: The nation’s first presidential caucus is always important, but with more than 20 Democrats running this time, the need for a strong showing is far more urgent.
snippet: The nation’s first presidential caucus is always important, but with more than 20 Democrats running this time, the need for a strong showing is far more urgent.
lead_paragraph: IOWA CITY — It may be nearly nine months until the first balloting of the 2020 primary, but candidates are already practically tripping over one another in Iowa.

abstract: The third annual Believer Festival was just the latest sign of life for a burgeoning books scene in the desert.
snippet: The third annual Believer Festival was just the latest sign of life for a burgeoning books scene in the desert.
lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — On a recent very warm Saturday afternoon, just a few blocks northeast of a string of ramshackle chapels offering Elvis-themed weddings on Las Vegas Boulevard, the novelist Tommy Orange was discussing the critical reception given to “There There,” his polyphonic novel about contemporary Native Americans.

abstract: As passengers fled a burning plane in Moscow, some stopped to get their luggage. Don’t be too quick to judge.
snippet: As passengers fled a burning plane in Moscow, some stopped to get their luggage. Don’t be too quick to judge.
lead_paragraph: Imagine trying to get out of a plane, but the passenger ahead of you is blocking the aisle as he tries to wrestle his carry-on free. Frustrating, right? And, oh — did we mention that the plane is on fire?

abstract: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
snippet: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
lead_paragraph: From the trade war with China to escalating tensions over the Mueller report, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).
headline_main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

abstract: Starting as a $40-a-week proofreader, he rose through the newsroom and corporate ranks, becoming chairman and chief executive of Dow Jones.
snippet: Starting as a $40-a-week proofreader, he rose through the newsroom and corporate ranks, becoming chairman and chief executive of Dow Jones.
lead_paragraph: Warren H. Phillips, who started at The Wall Street Journal as a $40-a-week proofreader and then vaulted through the ranks to become its publisher and the chief executive of its parent, Dow Jones & Company, died on Friday at his home in Bridgehampton, N.Y. He was 92.

abstract: In President Trump’s world, most sins are eventually forgiven except for one — profiting from his name.
snippet: In President Trump’s world, most sins are eventually forgiven except for one — profiting from his name.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Most people accepted into President Trump’s orbit usually end up encountering the same truism: Once you’re in, you’re in — and even when you’re down, you’re rarely out for good.

abstract: Ms. Pollan, who lives on Manhattan’s Upper East Side, spends time with her family cooking, going out to brunch and visiting art museums.
snippet: Ms. Pollan, who lives on Manhattan’s Upper East Side, spends time with her family cooking, going out to brunch and visiting art museums.
lead_paragraph: For Tracy Pollan, Sundays are about enjoying the city. “We’re super active as a family and get out and explore,” she said.
